# Settings & Environment Variables

## Complete `.env` Reference

```bash
# App
APP_NAME=ApplyPilot
DEBUG=false
BASE_URL=https://yourdomain.com  # Used in password-reset and verification emails
ALLOWED_HOSTS=yourdomain.com,www.yourdomain.com

# Security
JWT_SECRET=<32+ char, 3 char types min>
# Generate: python -c "import secrets; print(secrets.token_urlsafe(48))"
JWT_EXPIRATION_HOURS=24
BCRYPT_ROUNDS=12

# Encryption key for stored BYOK API keys (REQUIRED in production)
# Must be set BEFORE the first JWT_SECRET rotation to avoid losing stored keys.
# Generate: python -c "from cryptography.fernet import Fernet; print(Fernet.generate_key().decode())"
ENCRYPTION_KEY=<Fernet base64url key>

# Database
DATABASE_URL=postgresql+asyncpg://user:pass@host:5432/dbname

# Redis
REDIS_URL=redis://localhost:6379/0

# LLM — provider selection (default gemini)
# LLM_PROVIDER=gemini   # gemini | openai | anthropic | ollama
# Optional server-side Gemini key; Google rotates key formats (not only the legacy AIza… shape).
GEMINI_API_KEY=<your Gemini API key>
GEMINI_MODEL=gemini-3.5-flash

# LLM — Vertex AI (optional Gemini backend, server-admin only)
# USE_VERTEX_AI=true
# VERTEX_AI_PROJECT=your-gcp-project
# IMPORTANT: gemini-3-* models ONLY work with VERTEX_AI_LOCATION=global
# VERTEX_AI_LOCATION=global

# LLM — OpenAI (when LLM_PROVIDER=openai)
# OPENAI_API_KEY=
# OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-4o-mini

# LLM — Anthropic (when LLM_PROVIDER=anthropic)
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
# ANTHROPIC_MODEL=claude-sonnet-4-5

# LLM — Ollama local/self-hosted (when LLM_PROVIDER=ollama)
# OLLAMA_BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:11434
# OLLAMA_MODEL=llama3.2

# Google OAuth (optional)
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=xxx.apps.googleusercontent.com
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=GOCSPX-xxx

# Email (Gmail SMTP)
SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
SMTP_PORT=587
SMTP_USERNAME=you@gmail.com
SMTP_PASSWORD=<App Password>
SMTP_FROM_EMAIL=you@gmail.com
SMTP_FROM_NAME=ApplyPilot

# Analytics (optional — banner is hidden when POSTHOG_ENABLED=false)
POSTHOG_API_KEY=phc_xxx
POSTHOG_HOST=https://us.i.posthog.com
POSTHOG_ENABLED=false

# Security contact for /.well-known/security.txt (RFC 9116)
# Defaults to security@<BASE_URL domain> when not set.
# SECURITY_CONTACT_EMAIL=security@yourdomain.com

# Self-hosted flags
# Skip email verification — users auto-verified on registration.
# Required when SMTP is not configured. NOT safe for public multi-user deployments.
# DISABLE_EMAIL_VERIFICATION=true

# Logging
LOG_LEVEL=INFO
LOG_FORMAT=json    # always respected — not overridden by DEBUG mode
LOG_DIR=logs
LOG_FILE_ENABLED=true
```

## Settings Access Pattern
Always use the cached accessor — never instantiate `Settings()` directly:

```python
from config.settings import get_settings
settings = get_settings()  # Cached via @lru_cache
```

For tests that change env vars:
```python
from config.settings import clear_settings_cache
clear_settings_cache()
```

## BYOK — Google Gemini / AI Studio keys

**Users bring their own Google Gemini / Google AI Studio API keys** via Settings → AI Setup. Multi-provider BYOK (OpenAI/Anthropic user keys) is not in the Settings UI yet — non-Gemini providers use **server env keys** (`OPENAI_API_KEY`, `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, or local Ollama).

Gate helpers live in `utils/llm/availability.py`:
- `server_has_llm_credentials()` — True when the **active** `LLM_PROVIDER` has server credentials
- `effective_user_api_key(gemini_key)` — returns the BYOK key only when `LLM_PROVIDER=gemini` (never send a Gemini key to OpenAI/Anthropic)

There is no user-facing way to use Vertex AI — `USE_VERTEX_AI` is server-admin only.

**Format validation** is intentionally loose: `utils/gemini_api_key_format.validate_gemini_api_key()` (length bounds, single line, no whitespace, URL-safe / base64-style characters). The same helper validates optional `GEMINI_API_KEY` in `config/settings.py` and user keys in `api/profile.py`. Google may issue new key shapes over time; real validity is determined when the API is called.

Do **not** reintroduce an `AIza`-only or overly strict allowlist without a concrete breakage report — it will reject valid keys again.

## Startup Validators (enforced at settings load)
`config/settings.py` uses `@field_validator` to enforce these at startup — a bad value raises `ValueError` before the app starts:

| Setting | Validation |
|---------|-----------|
| `LLM_PROVIDER` | Must be one of: `gemini`, `openai`, `anthropic`, `ollama` |
| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | If set, must pass `validate_gemini_api_key()` (see `utils/gemini_api_key_format.py`) |
| `ENCRYPTION_KEY` | Must be a valid Fernet key (`Fernet(v)` check) |
| `JWT_SECRET` | Min 32 chars, 3 character types, no weak patterns |
| `DATABASE_URL` | Must start with `postgresql://` or `postgresql+asyncpg://` |
| `BASE_URL` | Must be HTTPS for non-localhost URLs in production |

**`BASE_URL` is especially important** — it is used to build password reset links and verification URLs. A non-HTTPS `BASE_URL` would silently serve these over plain HTTP.

## `SMTP_PASSWORD` — Must Use `SecretStr`
`SMTP_PASSWORD` is stored as `SecretStr` in settings. When passing to `smtplib`, always call `.get_secret_value()`:

```python
# ✅ Correct
server.login(self.smtp_username, self.smtp_password.get_secret_value())

# ❌ Wrong — logs as "**********" but fails
server.login(self.smtp_username, self.smtp_password)
```

This prevents the SMTP password from appearing in stack traces, debug output, or log lines.

## `ENCRYPTION_KEY` vs `JWT_SECRET`
- `JWT_SECRET` — signs JWT tokens; rotating it invalidates all active sessions.
- `ENCRYPTION_KEY` — Fernet key for encrypting stored BYOK API keys; can be rotated independently.
- If `ENCRYPTION_KEY` is absent, the app falls back to deriving a key from `JWT_SECRET` (backward compat). **This is unsafe for production** — if `JWT_SECRET` is rotated, every stored BYOK key becomes permanently unreadable.
- **Always set `ENCRYPTION_KEY` before deploying to production** and before any `JWT_SECRET` rotation.

## Redis TLS in Production
`REDIS_URL` must start with `rediss://` (double `s`) in any shared/production environment. Plain `redis://` transmits JWT blocklist entries, rate-limit counters, and session data in cleartext.

The startup guard in `main.py` raises `RuntimeError` if `is_production and not redis_url.startswith("rediss://")`.

## `.env` File Rules
- **Never commit `.env` to version control.** `.gitignore` already excludes it.
- **`.env.local.example`** is the published template — it **should** be committed. It contains only `REPLACE_WITH_*` placeholders and local-friendly defaults. `make start` copies it to `.env` on first run.
- If `.env` was ever committed to git, treat every secret in it as compromised and rotate immediately.
- `DEBUG` must be `false` in any shared / production environment. Setting `DEBUG=true` enables debug-only code paths (e.g., token logging) that are security risks.
- Verify `.gitignore` covers: `*.pem`, `*.key`, `*.p12`, `service_account*.json`, `credentials*.json`, `*.pfx`, `*.crt`, `*.cer`.

## `Settings.is_production` Property
```python
settings.is_production  # True when debug=False and testing=False
```
Use this (not raw env var checks) for conditional behavior.

## JWT Secret Validation Rules
- Minimum 32 characters
- At least 3 character types (lowercase, uppercase, digits, special)
- Rejected patterns: repeated sequences (e.g. `password` × 4)

## CORS Origins
Set `CORS_ORIGINS` to an explicit comma-separated list of allowed origins.
**Never use `*` in production.** There is no `disable_host_validation` escape hatch — configure origins explicitly.

```bash
# Development
CORS_ORIGINS=http://localhost:3000,http://localhost:8000

# Production (example)
CORS_ORIGINS=https://applypilot.yourdomain.com
```
